      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "*Hmph*, AC circuits, eh? Sounds like a proper tangle, much like a goblin horde trying to navigate a particularly muddy patch of bog. But fear not, for even the most convoluted goblin ambush can be mapped out with a bit of proper calculation!\n\nTo find the total impedance ($Z$), you need to combine the resistance ($R$) and the inductive reactance ($X_L$) using the Pythagorean theorem, just like a goblin chieftain calculates the optimal flanking maneuver—it's all about the right angles!\n\nHere are the steps, so you don't get lost in the goblin mire:\n\n**1. Calculate Total Impedance ($Z$):**\n\nThe formula for impedance in a series RL circuit is:\n$$Z = \\sqrt{R^2 + X_L^2}$$\n\nIn your case, you have $R = 50\\ \\Omega$ and $X_L = 30\\ \\Omega$.\n\n$$Z = \\sqrt{(50)^2 + (30)^2}$$\n$$Z = \\sqrt{2500 + 900}$$\n$$Z = \\sqrt{3400}$$\n$$Z \\approx 58.",
